Output 6

The â€œdata()â€ function is used to get a list of all the in-built datasets present in R. I chose the dataset â€œairqualityâ€, which consist of the daily readings of 4 air quality values (Ozone, Solar, Wind, Temp) in New York, from May to September 1973. The â€œhead()â€ function returns the first 10 rows of the dataset. To learn more about the attributes and definitions of the selected datatset, Iâ€™ve used the â€œhelp()â€ function.

Analysis 1: The summary() function is used to generate a summary of the variables in this dataset, including mean, median, min, max, and quartiles. Analysis 2: The ggplot() function is used to create a scatterplot, with Ozone on the x-axis and Solar Radiations on the y-axis, to observe the distribution of the data points and identify outliers. Analysis 3: The hist() function is used to create an histogram of the numerical variable Temp, to display the frequency of the datapoints within bins/intervals. Analysis 4: The cor() function is used to find the correlations between all the variables. From the output, it is observed that the correlation between Wind and Ozone is maximum and positive; it is also observed that the correlation between Temp and Ozone is maximum and negative. Analysis 5: Omitted the NA values, and created a kmeans model to perform clustering of the data. Then, used fviz_cluster to plot the clustering.

Conclusion

  1. I learnt to use the â€œgetwd()â€ function to get my current working directory. I used the â€œclass()â€ function to find the class of a variable.
  2. I learnt to create a vector and perform a few operations on the vector, like finding the length, retrieving an element from it, etc. I also learnt to create a matrix and combine matrices using â€œrbind()â€ and â€œcbind()â€ functions.
  3. Further, I learnt to work with in-built datasets in R-Studio. I performed different types of analyses on the â€œairqualityâ€ dataset. I summarized the dataset which produced the mean, median, min, max, and quartile values of each column in the dataset. I worked with scatterplots and histograms to observe the distribution of data points and explore relationships between different variables of the dataset.
  4. Using the abovementioned dataset, I also worked with the â€œcor()â€ function to find the correlation between different variables. Moreover, I learnt to create a kmeans model to perform clustering of data, and then plotted the clusters using â€œfviz_cluster()â€ function.
